### Cards

To display the results, I decided to use the cards layout, by using Vuetify&#39;s card component which the documentation for can be found [here](https://vuetifyjs.com/en/components/cards#card).

The first thing that was done was create a basic card layout, which I got from the documentation, and then replaced the image with result.picture.url from the Autoura API (this will show the images of the poi).

\&lt;v-img

                    _height_=&quot;200px&quot;

                    :_src_=&quot;result.picture.url&quot;

                    _v-if_=&quot;result.picture.url !==null&quot;

                  \&gt;

However, as you can see in the code above, if there is no image then it will = null and nothing will show.

Within the \&lt;v-container\&gt; there is a \&lt;span\&gt; which is where

_v-text_=&quot;result.name&quot;

is.  This displays the name of the poi from the Autoura API.

As mentioned earlier, accessible places had a toggle button. The cards display an accessible symbol IF the location is accessible. To do this I used one of Vuetify&#39;s card component v-card-actions. This allows a basic condition which is usually used to add and hide text until it&#39;s opened. However, I used it to show or hide the accessibility symbol by doing the following:

 \&lt;v-icon_v-if_=&quot;result.accessibility.wheelchair ==true&quot;\&gt;accessible\&lt;/v-icon\&gt;

As you can see if the result accessibility is true then display the accessible symbol. In supplement this there is also a button in a form of an arrow next to it which takes you to the next time.

\&lt;v-btn:_to_=&quot;&#39;/results/&#39;+searchPick.search +&#39;/&#39;+ result.stop\_id&quot;_icon_\&gt;

                      \&lt;v-icon\&gt;arrow\_right\_alt\&lt;/v-icon\&gt;

 \&lt;/v-btn\&gt;

The button is complimented by the following code which is in the script.

let link =

        &quot;https://api.autoura.com/api/stops/search?group\_context=&quot;+

        _this_.groupPick.search +

        &quot;&amp;stop\_types=&quot;+

        _this_.searchPick.search;

      if (_this_.wheelChair) {

        link = link +&quot;&amp;wheelchair=true&quot;;

      }

To break this down the url is [_https://api.autoura.com/api/stops/search?group\_context=_](https://api.autoura.com/api/stops/search?group_context=) and then it adds &quot;&amp;stop\_types=&quot; (this is searchPick) and grouptyp

# Methods

In this section I will be discussing what methods I used for this project, most notably Nuxt JS.

## Nuxt JS

Nuxt JS is a Vue.js framework which essentially is Vue js on steroids. To read more about Vue check out their official document [here.    ](https://nuxtjs.org/)

The reasons I chose to create this project using Nuxt are the following:

- Automatically add routes to the router.js file which saves a lot of time.
- During setup it allows you to easily choose the server, UI framework (such as Bootstrap) and testing framework (such as Jest) and add an axios module it allows HTTP requests easily in the application.

## Mapping and Geolocation

For mapping I used [_&#39;vue-google-maps&#39;_](https://www.npmjs.com/package/vue2-google-maps)as opposed to leafletJS  because Google Maps is more commonly used on websites. When setting up VueGoogleMaps I needed to go to the [Google Maps Platform Documentation](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/)

At this point, I needed to get an API key to put in the vue-google-maps.js file which I gotten from [here](https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/?apis=maps).

You can see in this code, how it is code. (Because of privacy reasons I have replaced the actual api key with xxxxxxxx).

import Vue from&#39;vue&#39;

import\*as VueGoogleMaps from&#39;vue2-google-maps&#39;

Vue.use(VueGoogleMaps, {

  load: {

    key:&#39;xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx&#39;,

  }

})



In the actual \_id.vue (the page with further information of selected), all I needed to do was this:

    \&lt;GmapMap

            :_center_=&quot;{lat:object.location.geocode.lat, lng:object.location.geocode.lng}&quot;

            :_zoom_=&quot;15&quot;

            _map-type-id_=&quot;terrain&quot;

            _style_=&quot;width: 100%; height: 500px&quot;

          \&gt;

            \&lt;GmapMarker

              :_position_=&quot;{lat:object.location.geocode.lat, lng:object.location.geocode.lng}&quot;

              :_clickable_=&quot;true&quot;

            /\&gt;

          \&lt;/GmapMap\&gt;

Which was similar to the quickstart on the npm vue2-leaflet-map, however for the position I needed to get the location of the POI from the API.

### Weather API

In addition to using the location from the API for the mapping, I thought instead of using firebase database, because I did not see how it fitted into my vision. I used [OpenWeatherMap&#39;s Weather API](https://openweathermap.org/api). I used this to show the weather of the selected POI. The weather API uses axios and then uses the lon and lat from the Autoura API.

getWeather() {

      _this_.$axios.get(&#39;https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?lat=&#39;+_this_.object.location.geocode.lat +&#39;&amp;lon=&#39;+_this_.object.location.geocode.lng +&#39;&amp;APPID=03bc9df889d6cf24f69ebed9ace4d15b&#39;)

      .then(_response_=\&gt; {

        _console_.log(&quot;Weather below&quot;);

        _console_.log(response)

        _this_.weather = response.data

      })

      .catch(_error_=\&gt; {

        _console_.log(error)

      })

    }
